<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF208-128-210  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 128 210.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Oct 2 1989 v3 n40 p22(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Digital scanning.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Shaw, Stephen J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Federal agencies are among the heaviest users of image scanningtechnology.andP;  Their lead is largely responsible for the latesttechnical and standards developments in that field.andP;  Thegovernment buys the most optical character readers (OCRs) in orderto cope with the massive amount of document processing it isrequired to do.andP;  The optical scanner market is expected to have acompound annual growth rate of 26 percent from 1989 to 1993.andO;Dealers expect to sell 347,000 scanners in 1990.andP;  Scanningtechnology is still evolving.andP;  OCRs still cannot read variabletypefaces or hand-written words.andP;  More advances are needed inaccuracy and speed.andP;  The advance in optical media technologyhinges largely on setting standards, which the government couldplay a key role in as a major user.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     National GovernmentScanningOptical Character ReadersDocument Management SystemsStandardsUser Needs.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   U.S. scanner market estimates (1989-1993). (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>